&= \frac{(\sqrt{2} - 1)^{2}}{1^{1 + \sqrt{3}}}\\
&= (\sqrt{2} - 1)^{2}\\
&= 2 - 2\sqrt{2} + 1\\
&= \boxed{3 - 2\sqrt{2}}.

We can use the point $(1,1)$ to solve for $b$:

\begin{align*}
1&=-1+b\\
\Rightarrow\qquad b&=2.
\end{align*}Therefore, $m+b=\boxed{1}$.

$$\frac{x}{a}+\frac{y}{b}+\frac{z}{c}=1.$$The center of the sphere passing through $A,$ $B,$ $C,$ and $O$ is the point where the plane and the sphere intersect.  The sphere has the equation

$$(x-p)^2+(y-q)^2+(z-r)^2=r^2.$$Setting these two equations equal to each other, we have

$$\frac{x}{a}+\frac{y}{b}+\frac{z}{c}=1\Rightarrow\frac{(x-p)^2}{a^2}+\frac{(y-q)^2}{b^2}+\frac{(z-r)^2}{c^2}=1.$$Expanding the left-hand side, we have

$$\frac{x^2-2px+p^2}{a^2}+\frac{y^2-2qy+q^2}{b^2}+\frac{z^2-2rz+r^2}{c^2}=1.$$Simplifying, we have

$$\frac{x^2}{a^2}+\frac{y^2}{b^2}+\frac{z^2}{c^2}-2\left(\frac{px}{a^2}+\frac{qy}{b^2}+\frac{rz}{c^2}\right)+p^2+q^2+r^2=1.$$Since $A,$ $B,$ and $C$ are distinct from $O,$ we have $a^2+b^2+c^2>0.$  Therefore, the above equation is equivalent to

$$\frac{p^2}{a^2}+\frac{q^2}{b^2}+\frac{r^2}{c^2}-2\left(\frac{px}{a^2}+\frac{qy}{b^2}+\frac{rz}{c^2}\right)=0.$$Since $p,$ $q,$ and $r$ are the coordinates of the center of the sphere, we have

$$\frac{p}{a}+\frac{q}{b}+\frac{r}{c}=2.$$Therefore, the answer is $\boxed{2}.$

Text to be judged: We have that

\begin{align*}
\log_{10} \sin x + \log_{10} \cos x &= -1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \log_{10} (\sin x \cos x) &= -1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x \cos x &= 10^{-1}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin 2x &= 2 \sin x \cos x = 2 \cdot 10^{-1}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin 2x &= 2 \cdot 10^{-1}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin 2x &= 0.2.
\end{align*}We also have that

\begin{align*}
\log_{10} (\sin x + \cos x) &= \frac{1}{2} (\log_{10} n - 1)\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x + \cos x &= 10^{\frac{1}{2} (\log_{10} n - 1)}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x + \cos x &= 10^{\frac{1}{2} \log_{10} n - \frac{1}{2}}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x + \cos x &= 10^{\frac{1}{2} \log_{10} n} \cdot 10^{-\frac{1}{2}}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x + \cos x &= \sqrt{n} \cdot \frac{1}{\sqrt{10}}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \sin x + \cos x &= \frac{\sqrt{n}}{\sqrt{10}}.
\end{align*}We can now use the identity $\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1$ to solve for $n$:

\begin{align*}
\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x &= 1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad (\sin x + \cos x)^2 - 2 \sin x \cos x &= 1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \left(\frac{\sqrt{n}}{\sqrt{10}}\right)^2 - 2 \cdot 10^{-1} &= 1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{n}{10} - 2 \cdot 10^{-1} &= 1\\
\Rightarrow\qquad \frac{n}{10} &= 1 + 2 \cdot 10^{-1}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad n &= 10 + 2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad n &= \boxed{12}.
\end{align*}
